#!CSeaGreen #!N  #!Rall288 Selecting a Choice in an Option Box #!N 
#!EC #!N #!N An option box contains a list of choices, 
but usually displays only the one currently selected. Option boxes are 
used throughout the Data Explorer interface. For example, the Selector interactor, 
illustrated in  #!Lobox50,dxall289 f Figure 50  #!EL  , can be displayed as an option box. 
#!N #!N Selecting a choice from this box is similar to 
selecting options from pull-down menus. To display the possible choices, click 
on the tab on the right side of the option box. 
With the list of choices displayed, click on your desired selection. 
The list of options disappears, and the option box is updated 
with the new selection. #!Cbrown #!N  #!F-adobe-times-medium-r-normal--18*    #!Robox50 #!N Graphics omitted 
from Online Documentation. Please see the manual. #!N #!N Figure 50. 
Example of an Option Box #!EF #!N #!EC #!N #!N Alternatively, 
you can select an option with the mouse by moving the 
cursor to the desired option box and pressing and holding the 
mouse button. The list of options appears. Then move the cursor 
to the desired option and release. Each option is highlighted as 
you move the cursor across it. #!N #!N Some of the 
options are accessible using accelerator keys. This is indicated to the 
right of the option in the options list, much like it 
is in the pull-down menus. #!N #!N #!N  #!F-adobe-times-medium-i-normal--18*   Next Topic 
